06838nam a22010455i 9783110197433DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082004gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)853269145  a97831101974337 a10.1515/97831101974332doi  a(DE-B1597)32214  a(OCoLC)816888370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP291 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a41522200aTriggers /ced. by Anne Breitbarth, Henk van Riemsdijk. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (496 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v750 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of 'trigger' is a core concept of Chomsky's Minimalist Program. The idea that certain types of movement are triggered by some property of the target position is at least as old as the notion that the movement of noun phrases to the subject position is triggered by their need to receive nominative case. In more recent versions of syntactic theory, triggering mechanisms are thought to regulate all of movement. Furthermore, a quite narrow range of triggering mechanisms is permitted. As is to be expected, such a restrictive approach meets a variety of difficulties. Specifically, the question is whether all triggering elements required to cover displacement of all kinds in natural language can be independently motivated. Further, how can a trigger theory, which crucially relies on the idea that all movement is obligatory, deal with apparently optional movement processes? Are features an adequate means to express the triggering function in all cases? More radically, are all movement phenomena really the result of the checking of trigger features? And what about apparent triggering factors that are 'external' to syntax such as prosody - can they be captured in a rigid trigger theory? In other words, could certain aspects of triggered movement be due to interface conditions? Such is the range of questions addressed by the fourteen contributions to this book. They cover a considerable range of languages (including Afrikaans, Breton, Bulgarian, Dutch, English, French, German, Gungbe, Hungarian, Italian, Japanese, Kiswahili, Romanian). These papers present materials, both empirical and theoretical, that will not fail to have considerable impact on the further development of the concept of trigger in syntactic theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 0aLinguistics. 0aSyntaxexTilburg <2002>. 4aMinimalistisches Programm. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aAboh, Enoch O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlboiu, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreitbarth, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreitbarth, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCollins, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorver, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinterhölzl, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawashima, Ruriko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKitahara, Hisatsugu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambova, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipták, Anikó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathieu, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator